-- PRESS DIGEST-Hong Kong - Nov 25
-- 
-- Mon Nov 24, 2014 08:33PM EST
-- None



Nov 25 (Reuters) - These are some of the leading stories in Hong Kong newspapers on Monday. Reuters has not verified these stories and does not vouch for their accuracy.

SOUTH CHINA MORNING POST  - About 3,000 police officers will be on standby this morning to help bailiffs enforce an injunction order to reopen the area of Argyle Street in Mong Kok occupied by democracy protesters. (http://bit.ly/1y9EUAL) - A proposal to extend the retirement age of newly hired civil servants will be submitted to the Executive Council soon so it can be introduced next year, government sources said. (http://bit.ly/1vH8TBf) - The trial of former chief secretary Rafael Hui Si-yan was taken on a journey of imagination and speculation as prosecutors tried to pin wrongdoing on the accused, the defence counsel said on Monday. (http://bit.ly/1uSGmXr)   THE STANDARD - Bailiffs, assisted by more than 3,000 police officers, are poised to clear barricades in the Mong Kok protest zone today, the scene of a series of violent clashes between Occupy Central supporters and opponents. (http://bit.ly/1C7ifJe) - A radical activist known as the "Frenchman", who allegedly led dozens of protesters to break into the Legislative Council complex, has been ordered to stay at least 300 metres away from the building in Tamar. (http://bit.ly/1xvA24Z) - It was Beijing that paid former chief secretary Rafael Hui Si-yan millions in 2007, instead of the Kwok brothers as alleged by the prosecution, a lawyer for defendant Francis Kwan Hung-sang maintained. (http://bit.ly/1C7ikNd)